As the population grows, the waste generated increases. This waste needs to be handled and recycled.\n","\n","The goal of our project is classifying recyclable waste materials based on images to their respecrtive appropriate recycle bins.\n","\n","We will examine diffrents network architectures to detrmine which one is best for the goal at hand.\n","\n","We tried several approches to tackle this challenge:\n","\n","1. Firstly, we tried a simplified VGG-style CNN network.\n","\n","2. Since we acheived only 70% accuracy, we aspired to use ResNet50 architecture. Since ResNet50 is a complex architecture which includes high amount of parameters, and we do not own the proper resources to train such complex architecture, we used pretrained model via Transfer learning. \n","\n","3. We tried to explore the usage of autoencoders to extract essential features out of each image and using the encoded images to train the VGG network, with the intent that reduced dimentionality would reduce training time with minimal effect to accuracy.\n","\n","4. We encountered a class-imbalanced dataset which affected the percision of certain classes predictions. To tackle the issue, we used 2 techniques and were able to increase the percision of these certain classes while maintaining an accuracy of 94% upon the test dataset.\n","\n","Further explanations and we used The Garbage Classification Dataset which contains 6 classifications:\n","1. Cardboard (403)\n","2. Glass (501)\n","3. Metal (410)\n","4. Paper(594)\n","5. Plastic (482) \n","6. Trash(137)\n","\n","As shown above, our dataset suffers from class imbalance especially towards the trash class.\n","\n","Example pictures for each category are shown below:\n","\n","![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","(Cardboard)![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","(Glass) ![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","(Metal)\n","\n","![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","(Paper)![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","(Plastic)![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","(Trash)\n"],"metadata":{"id":"KMIymzaLVgKK"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["The Dataset was provided by Kaggle [1].\n","\n","Sometimes there are scenarios where you have way lesser number of samples for some of the classes where as other classes have lots of samples. In such a scenario, you don’t want a training batch to be contain samples just from a few of the classes with lots of samples. \n","\n","Ideally, a training batch should contain represent a good spread of the dataset.\n","To overcome this issue we tried 2 techniques:\n","\n","The first one was to augment the undersmapled classes with added smaples via:  \n"," - Random presctive\n"," - Roandom rotation \n"," - Color jitter\n","\n","And the second was using a weighted classes method, where samples of each batch are chosen at random inversely proportional to each class amount . For example this technique will oversample the trash class images and downsample the paper class images since the first has only 137 images and the second has 594 images.\n","\n","[1] https://www.kaggle.com/c/stat440-20-module3/data\n","\n","![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)"],"metadata":{"id":"FmdQULFfY0I3"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Loading The 42\n","torch.manual_seed(random_seed)\n","train_ds, val_ds, test_ds = random_split(dataset, [1767, 380, 380])\n","len(train_ds), len(val_ds), len(test_ds)\n","\n","batch_size = 32\n","train_dl = batches:"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"id":"fN1C5NaawRgM"},"outputs":[],"source":["from torchvision.utils import make_grid\n","\n","def show_batch(dl):\n","    images, labels = next(iter(dl))\n","    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 6))\n","    ax.set_xticks([])\n","    ax.set_yticks([])\n","    ax.imshow(make_grid(images, nrow = 16).permute(1, 2, 0))\n"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Displaying Example Batch**"],"metadata":{"id":"6FoLhEkE84c0"}},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":115},"executionInfo":{"elapsed":2545,"status":"ok","timestamp":1645699694003,"user":{"displayName":"RavIla","photoUrl":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/default-user=s64","userId":"14384815220194720162"},"user_tz":-120},"id":"8EUwjiuHwRgN","outputId":"b87c31d8-289a-4071-88e0-f82fe0b764b5"},"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"image/png":"\n","text/plain":["<Figure size 864x432 with 1 Axes>"]},"metadata":{}}],"source":["show_batch(test_dl)"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"a9LkCrj1wRgP"},"source":["**Porting to GPU**\n","\n","GPUs tend to perform faster calculations than CPU. "]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"id":"30bmllqDwRgQ"},"outputs":[],"source":["def get_default_device():\n","    \"\"\"Pick GPU if available, else CPU\"\"\"\n","    if torch.cuda.is_available():\n","        return torch.device('cuda')\n","    else:\n","        return torch.device('cpu')\n","    \n","def to_device(data, device):\n","    \"\"\"Move tensor(s) to chosen device\"\"\"\n","    if isinstance(data, (list,tuple)):\n","        return [to_device(x, device) for x in data]\n","    return data.to(device, non_blocking=True)\n","\n","class DeviceDataLoader():\n","    \"\"\"Wrap a dataloader to move data to a device\"\"\"\n","    def __init__(self, dl, device):\n","        self.dl = dl\n","        self.device = device\n","        \n","    def __iter__(self):\n","        \"\"\"Yield a batch of data after moving it to device\"\"\"\n","        for b in self.dl: \n","            yield to_device(b, self.device)\n","\n","    def __len__(self):\n","        \"\"\"Number of batches\"\"\"\n","        return len(self.dl)"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"id":"TdxXubquwRgR"},"outputs":[],"source":["device = get_default_device()\n","\n","train_dl = DeviceDataLoader(train_dl, device)\n","val_dl = DeviceDataLoader(val_dl, device)\n","test_dl = DeviceDataLoader(test_dl, device)"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["# Network"],"metadata":{"id":"KS5AvTv04kRz"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"9-lv4uVLwRgN"},"source":["## Architectures"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["\n","**CNN (VGG) Class**"],"metadata":{"id":"ISA9Tdb9BXNX"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["VGG-Network is a convolutional neural network model proposed by K. Simonyan and A. Zisserman in the paper “Very Deep Convolutional Networks for Large-Scale Image Recognition” [1].\n","\n","We implemented a VGG-like architecture using the same guiding principles of a classic VGG architecture.\n","The principles includes: increasing the number of channels, and reducing the image's dimensions simulationusly in each layer.\n","In order to improve the stablization of the network, we used Batch Normalization in each block. \n","\n","Our VGG-like architecture is shown in the picture below:\n","\n","[1]. K. Simonyan and A. Zisserman: Very Deep Convolutional Networks for Large-Scale Image Recognition, April 2015, DOI: https://arxiv.org/pdf/1409.1556.pdf\n","\n","![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n"],"metadata":{"id":"0qecEYOvzbow"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["class VGG(nn.Module):\n","    def __init__(self, n=32, k=3, classes=6, image_size=256):\n","        super(VGG, self).__init__()\n","        self.n = n\n","        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=3, out_channels=n, kernel_size=3, padding='same')\n","        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=n, out_channels=2*n, kernel_size=3, padding='same')\n","        self.conv3 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=2*n, out_channels=4*n, kernel_size=3, padding='same')\n","        self.conv4 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=4*n, out_channels=8*n, kernel_size=3, padding='same')\n","        self.maxpool = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)\n","        self.bn1=nn.BatchNorm2d(n)\n","        self.bn2=nn.BatchNorm2d(2*n)\n","        self.bn3=nn.BatchNorm2d(4*n)\n","        self.bn4=nn.BatchNorm2d(8*n)  \n","        \n","        #256/(2**4)**2=32, 256, 16, 16\n","        # image at final layer == 256/2**4 => 16x16\n","\n","        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(8*n*16*16 , 4096)\n","        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(4096, classes)\n","\n","    def forward(self, x):\n","        # Block 1\n","        x = self.conv1(x)\n","        x = F.relu(x)\n","        x = self.maxpool(x)\n","        x = self.bn1(x)\n","\n","        # Block 2\n","        x = self.conv2(x)\n","        x = F.relu(x)\n","        x = self.maxpool(x)\n","        x = self.bn2(x)\n","\n","        # Block 3\n","        x = self.conv3(x)\n","        x = F.relu(x)\n","        x = self.maxpool(x)\n","        x = self.bn3(x)\n","\n","        # Block 4\n","        x = self.conv4(x)\n","        x = F.relu(x)\n","        x = self.maxpool(x)\n","        x = self.bn4(x)\n","        \n","        x = x.view(-1, 8*self.n*16*16)\n","        x = self.fc1(x)\n","        x = F.relu(x)\n","\n","        #dropout was included to combat overfitting\n","        x = F.dropout(x, 0.5) \n","        x = self.fc2(x)\n","        return x\n"],"metadata":{"id":"azbWHFT9yITm"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Autoencoder Class** "],"metadata":{"id":"SEckmFDABM0p"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Given the fact that State-of-the-art architectures for image classification such as ResNet and VGG are usually deep and complex, and include many parameters, they may take longer times to train than other networks.\n","\n","We tried experimenting with autoencoders to reduce the dimentionality of the input we can feed to our networks.\n","By reducingthe the size and dimentionality of the input we would be able to use SMALLER networks, with fewer parameters to train (e.g in the VGG class we were able bypass two whole blocks and feed the encoded input stright into the third block).\n","\n","Since the inputs are images we wanted to implement the Autoencoder using only convolution and de-convolution layers as to not lose the advantages of locality.  \n","\n","The De-convolution layer's objective is to undo the result of a prior convolution, and unlike the convolutional layer, it's upsampling in nature. De-convolutions are usually used in auto-encoders and GANs, or generally any network that must reconstruct an image.\n","\n","more info about De-convolution:\n","https://cs.nyu.edu/~fergus/drafts/utexas2.pdf\n","\n","We passed the data through an Encoder and Decoder, with skip connections between the layers as shown:\n","![image.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","\n","\n","The encoding is validated and refined by attempting to regenerate the input from the encoding. The autoencoder learns a representation (encoding) for a set of data, with dimensionality reduction, by training the network to ignore insignificant data. \n","We added skip connections in an attempt to force the network to maintain the locality.\n","\n","After training we passed the encoded images to a second network (VGG) to examine classification quality.\n","\n","Since essential features of every image are embedded within the encoded images, we expected to receive the added benefit of reduced dimensionality included with a relative high accuracy.\n","\n","Results are in the \"Benchmarks And Results\""],"metadata":{"id":"D0NMV0RVmeMn"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["class autoencoder(nn.Module):\n","    def __init__(self):\n","        super(autoencoder, self).__init__()\n","        \n","        self.encoder1 = nn.Sequential(\n","            nn.Conv2d(3, 6, 3, stride=2, padding=1),\n","            nn.ReLU(),\n","            )\n","        self.encoder2 = nn.Sequential(\n","            nn.Conv2d(6, 12, 3, stride=2, padding=1),\n","            nn.ReLU(),\n","            )\n","        self.encoder3 = nn.Conv2d(12, 24, 3, stride=2, padding=1)\n","      \n","\n","        self.decoder1 = nn.Sequential(\n","            nn.ConvTranspose2d(24, 12, 3, stride=2, padding=1, output_padding=1),\n","            nn.ReLU(),\n","            )\n","        self.decoder2 =  nn.Sequential(\n","            nn.ConvTranspose2d(12, 6, 3, stride=2, padding=1, output_padding=1),\n","            nn.ReLU(),\n","            )\n","        self.decoder3 =  nn.Sequential( \n","            nn.ConvTranspose2d(6, 3, 3, stride=2, padding=1, output_padding=1),\n","            nn.Sigmoid()\n","            )\n","            \n","    def forward(self, x):\n","        encoded1 = self.encoder1(x)\n","        encoded2 = self.encoder2(encoded1)\n","        encoded = self.encoder3(encoded2)\n","\n","        decoded1 = self.decoder1(encoded) + encoded2\n","        decoded2 = self.decoder2(decoded1) +encoded1\n","        decoded = self.decoder3(decoded2)\n","        \n","        return decoded, encoded"],"metadata":{"id":"oDZBP6MyyKgt"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Encoded VGG Class**\n","\n","This VGG class is designed to receive as input an enncoded images that was outputed out of a trained and fixed Encoder. \n","\n","It Has Similar architecture to the previous VGG class but is REDUCED in size. Two convolution blocks were REMOVED. The number of output channels in the remaining ones were reduced as well to accommodate the number of channels in the encoded image input. \n","\n","In short, we tarined an autoencoder to encode an image to a reduced representation with equal dimenstions (hight,width,channeles) as the third block of the original VGG, so essentially the first two blocks of the VGG can be bypassed.  See sketch below\n","\n","![cpu architecture hardware design - Page 1 (2).png](data:image/png;base64,)\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"HOpf5NP6iq3U"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["class VGG_encoded(nn.Module):\n","    def __init__(self, classes=6):\n","        super(VGG_encoded, self).__init__()\n","\n","        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=24, out_channels=64, kernel_size=3, padding='same')\n","        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=64, out_channels=128, kernel_size=3, padding='same')\n","\n","        self.maxpool = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)\n","        self.bn1=nn.BatchNorm2d(64)\n","        self.bn2=nn.BatchNorm2d(128) \n","        \n","        self.fc1 = nn.Linear(128*8*8 , 4096)\n","        self.fc2 = nn.Linear(4096, classes)\n","\n","    def forward(self, x):\n","        # Block 1\n","        x = self.conv1(x)\n","        x = F.relu(x)\n","        x = self.maxpool(x)\n","        x = self.bn1(x)\n","\n","        # Block 2\n","        x = self.conv2(x)\n","        x = F.relu(x)\n","        x = self.maxpool(x)\n","        x = self.bn2(x)\n","         \n","        x = x.flatten(start_dim=1)\n","        x = self.fc1(x)\n","        x = F.relu(x)\n","\n","        #dropout was included to combat overfitting\n","        x = F.dropout(x, 0.5) \n","        x = self.fc2(x)\n","        return x\n"],"metadata":{"id":"d44ys-NC99_R"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**ResNet Class**"],"metadata":{"id":"2QyycKzXBURx"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["A residual neural network (ResNet) is an artificial neural network (ANN) of a kind that builds on constructs known from pyramidal cells in the cerebral cortex. Residual neural networks do this by utilizing skip connections, or shortcuts to jump over some layers. Typical ResNet models are implemented with double- or triple- layer skips that contain nonlinearities (ReLU) and batch normalization in between.\n","\n","As taught in class, Residual Netowrk includes skip connections to avoid the problem of vanishing gradients. Skip connections also ensures the identical mapping is reachable in ech layer, allowing the NN to adjust the network or cancelling a layer if one is degrading the network performance via skipping it and settings it's weights to 0.\n","\n","We used Resnet50 architecture which includes 50 layers. Since this architecture is complex, and we do not have the proper resources to train it, we used a pretrained model via Transfer Learning methods.\n","\n","* Furthermore can be read in the Results section."],"metadata":{"id":"YNR0AyMFzTtH"}},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"id":"K7yg-AztwRgP"},"outputs":[],"source":["class ResNet(nn.Module):\n","    def __init__(self, tl_mode='fixed', n=512):\n","        super().__init__()\n","        # Use a pretrained model\n","        self.network = torchvision.models.resnet50(pretrained=True)\n","        num_ftrs = self.network.fc.in_features\n","        # ConvNet as fixed feature extractor mode\n","        if tl_mode=='fixed':\n","          # Fixing the Resnet-50 Layers\n","          for param in self.network.parameters():\n","            param.requires_grad = False\n","          \n","          trail_nn = nn.Sequential(\n","              nn.Linear(num_ftrs, 512), nn.ReLU(),\n","              nn.Linear(512, 64), nn.ReLU(),\n","              nn.Linear(64, 16), nn.ReLU(),\n","              nn.Linear(16, len(classes)))\n","        else:\n","          # Fine-tuning ConvNet mode\n","          trail_nn = nn.Linear(num_ftrs, len(classes))\n","\n","        # Replace last layer\n","        self.network.fc = trail_nn\n","            \n","    def forward(self, xb):\n","        return torch.sigmoid(self.network(xb))\n","   "]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["##Transfer Learning\n","Transfer learning (TL) is a research problem in machine learning (ML) that focuses on storing knowledge gained while solving one problem and applying it to a different but related problem. For example, using a pretrained model which was trained for classification upon a certain dataset to solve a classification problem upon a different dataset.\n","\n","Even though skip connections make it possible to train extremely deep networks, it is still a tedious process to train these complex networks and it requires a huge amount of data.  Moreover, it was shown that some datasets  do not lead to convergence and acceptable accuracies.\n","\n","By using transfer learning [1] it is possible to load a pretrained convolutional weights and train a different classifier on top of it.\n","We examined two Transfer learning scenarios using a pre trained ResNet50 model:\n","-\tResNet50 as fixed feature extractor - We took a ResNet50 pretrained on ImageNet, removed the last fully connected layer and replace it with several fully connected layers. In the training process we fixed the the ResNet layers via using no-grad upon the ResNet Layers only, and therefore trained only the last fully connected layers.\n","-\tFine-tuning ResNet50 - in this strategy we replaced the last layer of the ResNet50 network with fully connected layers, similarly to the prior strategy,  but retrained all the network for several epochs without fixing any weights parameters.\n","The \"Resnet\" class we implemented supports both ostrategies via the 'tl_mode' parameter which can be set either to 'fixed' or to 'tuning'.\n","\n","[1]  https://cs231n.github.io/transfer-learning/#tf \n","\n","[2] https://pytorch.org/tutorials/beginner/transfer_learning_tutorial.html\n"],"metadata":{"id":"FF-Ln_nI8K2j"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## Losses\n","\n","1) AutoEncoder Loss:\n","\n","We used 2 type of loss functions.\n","In order to train the AutoEncoder we examined the usage of Mean Square Error (MSE) and Binary Cross Entropy (BCE) loss. We chose the second, since it produced better results.\n","\n","2) Model's Loss:\n","We used Cross Entropy (CE) upon the rest of the models."],"metadata":{"id":"l9cVdTiY4b2I"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## Optimizers\n","\n","1) We used the Adam optimizer in our models. \n","\n","2) We used a learning rate decay object which decreases the learning rate of the optimizer by a factor of 10 every 10 epochs.\n"],"metadata":{"id":"OidWhA094iZ7"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Learning Rates Decay**\n","\n","When training deep neural networks, it is often useful to reduce learning rate as the training progresses. This can be done by using pre-defined learning rate schedules or adaptive learning rate methods. It is usually best to perform high steps in the first epochs, since we didn't reach the loss surface's minimum and we want to advance quickly towards minimum. Although in advanced epochs, when the minimum is almost reached, we aspire to decrease the step's size to acheive accurate convergence towards the minimum."],"metadata":{"id":"8BG08CTW5Hyf"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","metadata":{"id":"YbTDwj-JwRgR"},"source":["## Training the Models"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["In order to train all these architectures we used train_model function which includes a mode parameter.\n","\n","The train_model function supports 3 modes:\n","\n","1. model - The function trains a classic NN model\n","2. autoencoder - The function trains an AutoEncoder model\n","3. encoder - The function is training a model using encoded images instead of the true images.\n","\n","The evaluate function evalutes the model upon the validation dataset.\n","\n","The parameters were chosen according to a grid search similar to a one we implemented in previous assignments"],"metadata":{"id":"ajPH_Bv8zzv3"}},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"id":"AbNAnj4FwRgO"},"outputs":[],"source":["def calc_accuracy(outputs, labels):\n","    _, preds = torch.max(outputs, dim=1)\n","    return torch.tensor(torch.sum(preds == labels).item() / len(preds))"]},{"cell_type":"code","execution_count":null,"metadata":{"id":"fQuPs6AowRgR"},"outputs":[],"source":["@torch.no_grad()\n","def evaluate( model,name, vl_loader, mode, autoencoder=None):\n","  \"\"\"\n","  Evaluate a model upon a validation DataLoader, the function calculates the\n","  accuracy and loss for each architecture depends on the mode.\n","  in mode='encoder', an autoencoder object must be supplied.\n","  \"\"\"\n","  model.eval()\n","  outputs = []\n","  for batch in vl_loader:\n","      images, labels = batch        \n","          \n","      if mode == 'model':\n","        # Evaluation upon a NN architecture\n","        out = model.forward(images)\n","        acc = calc_accuracy(out, labels)          \n","        loss = F.cross_entropy(out, labels)\n","\n","      elif mode=='autoencoder':\n","        # Evaluation upon an AutoEncoder architecture \n","        out, _ = model.forward(images)\n","        loss = F.binary_cross_entropy(out, images)\n","        acc = torch.Tensor([-1])\n","\n","      elif mode =='encoder':\n","        # Evaluation upon a NN using enocded images\n","        _, encoded_images = autoencoder.forward(images)\n","        out = model.forward(encoded_images)\n","        loss = F.cross_entropy(out, labels)\n","        acc = calc_accuracy(out, labels)          \n","\n","      outputs.append({'{}_loss'.format(name): loss.detach(), '{}_acc'.format(name): acc})\n","\n","  # average up the accuracy & loss upon all epochs\n","  epoch_loss = torch.stack(list(map(lambda x: x['{}_loss'.format(name)], outputs))).mean()   \n","  epoch_acc = torch.stack(list(map(lambda x: x['{}_acc'.format(name)], outputs))).mean()   \n","  return {'{}_loss'.format(name): epoch_loss.item(), '{}_acc'.format(name): epoch_acc.item()}\n","\n","\n","def train_model(name, epochs, model, train_loader, val_loader, optimizer, scheduler=None, autoencoder=None, mode='model'):\n","    \"\"\"\n","    Train a model upon a train DataLoader, the function calculates the\n","    accuracy and loss for each architecture depends on the mode.\n","    in mode='encoder', an autoencoder object must be supplied.\n","    \"\"\"\n","    history = []\n","    best_acc = 0\n","    min_loss = 100\n","\n","    for epoch in range(epochs):\n","        model.train()\n","        # Training Phase \n","        train_losses = []\n","        train_acc = []\n","        for batch in train_loader:\n","            images, labels = batch \n","            \n","            if mode=='autoencoder':\n","              # Training an AutoEncoder architecture via using BCE loss\n","              outputs, _ = model.forward(images)\n","              loss_func = F.binary_cross_entropy\n","              train_loss = loss_func(outputs, images)\n","            else:\n","              # Training a regular NN model using encoded images via a pretrained Encoder\n","              loss_func = F.cross_entropy\n","              if mode=='encoder':\n","                _, encoded_images = autoencoder.forward(images)\n","                outputs = model.forward(encoded_images) #.flatten(start_dim=1)\n","\n","              else:\n","                # Train a classic NN Model without any AutoEncoder included.\n","                outputs = model.forward(images)\n","              train_loss = loss_func(outputs, labels)\n","\n","              train_accuracy = calc_accuracy(outputs, labels)\n","              # History Tracking\n","              train_acc.append(train_accuracy)\n","            \n","\n","            train_losses.append(train_loss)\n","            # Backprop & update weights\n","            train_loss.backward()\n","            optimizer.step()\n","            # Cleanup\n","            optimizer.zero_grad()\n","\n","        # Learning rate decay\n","        if scheduler:\n","          scheduler.step()\n","\n","        # Finished an epoch, calculate the validation accuracy\n","\n","        result = evaluate(model,'val', val_loader, mode=mode, autoencoder=autoencoder) #results holds both train and val\n","        result['train_loss'] = torch.stack(train_losses).mean().item()\n","        temp_acc = float(result['val_acc'])\n","        temp_loss = float(result['val_loss'])\n","\n","        \n","        # test_result = evaluate(model,'test', test_loader, loss_func, mode=mode, autoencoder=autoencoder)  #test_results holds only test\n","        # temp_acc = float(test_result['test_acc'])\n","\n","        if mode=='autoencoder':\n","          result['train_acc'] = -1\n","        else:\n","          result['train_acc'] = torch.stack(train_acc).mean().item()\n","          \n","        if mode=='autoencoder':\n","          print(\"Epoch {}: train_loss: {:.4f}, val_loss: {:.4f}\".format( #, test_loss: {:.4f}\n","              epoch+1, result['train_loss'], result['val_loss'] ))  #, test_result['test_loss']\n","          if temp_loss < min_loss : \n","              min_loss = temp_loss\n","              torch.save(model,'/content/drive/MyDrive/DNN final/checkpoints/{}_trained_epoch{}_loss{:.4f}.pt'.format(name,epoch,min_loss))         \n","        else:\n","           \n","          print(\"Epoch {}: train_loss: {:.4f}, train_acc: {:.4f}, val_loss: {:.4f}, val_acc: {:.4f} \".format( #, test_loss: {:.4f}, test_acc: {:.4f}\n","              epoch+1, result['train_loss'], result['train_acc'], result['val_loss'], result['val_acc'])) #,test_result['test_loss'], test_result['test_acc']\n","          if  temp_acc > best_acc : \n","              best_acc =  temp_acc\n","              torch.save(model,'/content/drive/MyDrive/DNN final/checkpoints/{}_trained_epoch{}_acc{:.4f}.pt'.format(name,epoch,best_acc))\n","        history.append(result)\n","\n","    return history"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**VGG (title, history) in enumerate(histories.items()):\n","    plt.figure()\n","    plt.plot([x['val_acc'] for x in history], '-rx')\n","    plt.plot([x['train_acc'] for x in history], '-bo')\n"," sn.set_theme(style=\"whitegrid\")\n","    sn.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(14,7)})"]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Plot Confusion Matrix"],"metadata":{"id":"zoGPtq2e2xqX"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["def create_confusion_matrix(model, data_loader, num_of_classes=6,norm_axis=1, autoencoder=None):\n","    confusion_mat= np.zeros((len(classes),len(classes)))\n","    for batch in data_loader:\n","        images, labels_idx = batch\n","\n","        if autoencoder:\n","          x, images = autoencoder(images)\n","          images = images\n","\n","\n","        predications = model(images)\n","        pred_labels = torch.argmax(predications, dim=1)\n","        for pred, label in zip(pred_labels, labels_idx):\n","          confusion_mat[label.item(), pred.item()]+=1\n","        \n","    confusion_mat = confusion_mat/confusion_mat.sum(axis=norm_axis,keepdims=norm_axis)\n","    return confusion_mat\n","\n","def plot_confusion_matrix(models, data_loader, num_of_classes=6,norm_axis=1):\n","  for idx, (title, model) in enumerate(models.items()):\n","    if title=='Encoded VGG':\n","      mode = 'encoder'\n","      autoencoder = torch.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/DNN final/checkpoints/original data/model_autoencoder_trained_epoch19_loss0.5499.pt')\n","      confusion_matrix = create_confusion_matrix(model, data_loader,autoencoder=autoencoder)\n","    else:\n","      confusion_matrix = create_confusion_matrix(model, data_loader)\n","    \n","    df_cm = pd.DataFrame(confusion_matrix, index = classes,\n","                         columns = classes)    \n","    \n","    plt.figure(figsize=(12,7))\n","    plt.title('{}'.format(title));\n","    ax =sn.heatmap(df_cm,annot = True)\n","    ax.set(ylabel=\"Reference Label\", xlabel=\"Predicted Label\")\n","\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"aF9erxLsPeCn"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Plot to achieve 94% accuracy rate vs ~72% of the fixed method. \n","\n","**Fixed Resnet50 vs. Fine-Tuning Resnet50:**\n","\n","It is important to emphasize that these pre-trained models were trained upon ImageNet which includes millions of images which belongs to 1000 classes. \n","Although our Garbage dataset do not contains any animals and greatly differs from ImageNet, some of the garbage items share similar properties to ImageNet items. \n","\n","Properties such as: items which share a certain shape or items which includes a certain background. \n","\n","We anticipated that a fine-tuning model will perform better since it  adapts the model to our dataset in a better way while utilizing the feature extraction abilities of the pre-trained model and maximize it performance via training it to predict our garbage dataset.\n","\n"],"metadata":{"id":"KdbSFlJlW25L"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["**Percision assessment vs. Accuracy measurements**\n","\n","Precision for Multi-Class Classification\n","\n","In an imbalanced classification problem with more than two classes, precision is calculated as the sum of true positives across all classes divided by the sum of true positives and false positives across all classes.\n","\n","Classification accuracy alone can be misleading.\n","For us to get a better understanding of the networks performance we plotted a \"percision-confusion matrix\" where we can assess the prediction results more accurately.\n","\n","We can use this plot to get an idea of where our classifier got confused when making predictions.\n","\n","Confusion Matrix structure:\n","\n","The y axis represents the model's label prediction and the x axis  represents the ground-truth label. The cells are normalized to present the percision value of each cell.\n","Precision quantifies the number of positive class predictions that actually belong to the positive class.\n","\n","Further expalanation:\n","\n","https://machinelearningmastery.com/precision-recall-and-f-measure-for-imbalanced-classification/#:~:text=Precision%20quantifies%20the%20number%20of,and%20recall%20in%20one%20number."],"metadata":{"id":"jn_h_ELUYR9i"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plot_confusion_matrix({\"ResNet50 Fixed\": model_fx_original,\"ResNet50 Fine-Tuned\": model_ft_original}, test_dl)"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":911},"id":"YXiwZy7FVOWe","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1645700866360,"user_tz":-120,"elapsed":5329,"user":{"displayName":"RavIla","photoUrl":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/default-user=s64","userId":"14384815220194720162"}},"outputId":"628410d9-3c4d-403e-8449-153484252e1a"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"image/png":"\n","text/plain":["<Figure size 864x504 with 2 Axes>"]},"metadata":{}},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"image/png":"\n","text/plain":["<Figure size 864x504 with 2 Axes>"]},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Right away we can see our models are hard to classify the TRASH class.  Going over images of this class it is not hard to see why. The \"trash\" class contains images of items which are not recyclable but share similar features with items which are recyclable. \n","\n","Foil paper, for example, can easily be mistaken to be in the \"Metal\" class as it shares many features with metal such as color or reflectivity, rapping paper can easily be mislabeled as part of the \"Paper\" class etc.\n","Paper and Cardboard also get mixed up.\n","\n","We think this might be caused by the fact that the data is imbalanced and that there aren't enough Trash samples for the network to properly distinguish them from other classes. \n"],"metadata":{"id":"8M7LQvcCYget"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["As mentioned in the \"DATASET\" section in the begining we used \n","two approches to mitigate the data set problem:\n"," -  Augmenting the undersmapled classes with added smaples \n"," - Using a weighted classes method  \n","\n","We chose to continue with the second approach, since it had better results (results of first approach not shown)\n","\n","The second approach is using RandomWeightedSampler which balances the batches via over/under sampling of certain classes. \n","To do so, we count how many images are from each class and create a weight vector.\n","Each item is instantiated via the following formula: \\begin{equation} weight_i = \\frac{1}{count(class_i)} \\end{equation}\n","Therefore, in case we have a certain class with less images, such as “trash” it’s weight will be higher, and therefore the RandomWeightSampler will perform oversampling to the trash class\n","\n","More information here:\n","\n","https://androidkt.com/deal-with-an-imbalanced-dataset-using-weightedrandomsampler-in-pytorch/\n"],"metadata":{"id":"M-EQFtw8WbSh"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["random_seed = 42\n","torch.manual_seed(random_seed)\n","train_ds, val_ds, test_ds = random_split(dataset, [1767, 380, 380])\n","\n","from torch.utils.data import WeightedRandomSampler\n","\n","samplers = []           \n","\n","y_train_indices = train_ds.indices\n","y_train = [dataset.targets[i] for i in y_train_indices]\n","class_sample_count = np.array([len(np.where(y_train == t)[0]) for t in np.unique(y_train)])\n","weight = 1 / class_sample_count\n","samples_weight = np.array([weight[t] for t in y_train])\n","samples_weight = torch.from_numpy(samples_weight)\n","train_sampler = WeightedRandomSampler(samples_weight.type('torch.DoubleTensor'), len(samples_weight))\n","\n","                        \n","batch_size = 32\n","train_dl = DataLoader(train_ds, batch_size, num_workers = 4,sampler=train_sampler, pin_memory = True)\n","val_dl = DataLoader(val_ds, batch_size*2, num_workers = 4, pin_memory = True)\n","test_dl = DataLoader(test_ds, batch_size, num_workers = 4, pin_memory = True)\n","\n","device = get_default_device()\n","train_dl = DeviceDataLoader(train_dl, device)\n","val_dl = DeviceDataLoader(val_dl, device)\n","test_dl = DeviceDataLoader(test_dl, device)"],"metadata":{"id":"EXxxaiw8Ivzb"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["Loading best models and histories after training with the weighted classes:"],"metadata":{"id":"mdKUTz2VVAhB"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["model_VGG_weighted =torch.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/DNN final/checkpoints/weighted/model_vgg_trained_epoch16_acc0.7717.pt')\n","model_VGG_weighted = to_device(model_VGG_weighted, device)\n","to_device(model_VGG_weighted, device)\n","\n","model_ft_weighted =torch.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/DNN final/checkpoints/weighted/model_ft_trained_epoch15_acc0.9269.pt')\n","model_ft_weighted = to_device(model_ft_weighted, device)\n","to_device(model_ft_weighted, device)\n","\n","model_fix_weighted = torch.load('/content/drive/MyDrive/DNN final/checkpoints/weighted/model_fx_trained_epoch17_acc0.8236.pt')\n","model_fix_weighted = to_device(model_fix_weighted, device)\n","to_device(model_fix_weighted, device)"],"metadata":{"id":"nfIdgi9KRj4S"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[]},{"cell_type":"code","source":["plot_confusion_matrix({\"ResNet50 Fixed With Weighted Classes\": model_fix_weighted,\"ResNet50 Fine-Tuned With Weighted Classes\": model_ft_weighted}, test_dl)"],"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":911},"id":"Rxm7IQ9gbBSG","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1645701020868,"user_tz":-120,"elapsed":6376,"user":{"displayName":"RavIla","photoUrl":"https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/a/default-user=s64","userId":"14384815220194720162"}},"outputId":"541bd016-8650-48b3-9788-42245ed8933b"},"execution_count":null,"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"image/png":"\n","text/plain":["<Figure size 864x504 with 2 Axes>"]},"metadata":{}},{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"image/png":"\n","text/plain":["<Figure size 864x504 with 2 Axes>"]},"metadata":{}}]},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["We were able to achieved a 10% increase in trash to trash detection in the Fine-Tuned ResNet, with minimal decrease to the other classes' detection. \n","\n","The decrease to the other classes can be explained by the fact that over sampeling one class means that for a fixed batch size of other classes get \"undersmapled\".\n","\n","The Fixed ResNet network showed a tremendous improvment and Trash on Trash detection went up from 0 to 0.5!
